{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17654296","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17654296"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:51:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:51:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18613"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18613","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18613"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11345"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76434"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11345","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11345"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18613"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61931"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10278"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26332"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26339"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76434","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76434"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESkeletal muscle contains different fibre types with distinct metabolic and contractile properties. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a characteristic of fast glycolytic muscle fibres?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Slow myosin ATPase activity","High fatigue resistance","Predominant oxidative metabolism","Rapid contraction speed with low fatigue resistance","Large mitochondrial content"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERapid contraction speed with low fatigue resistance\u003C/strong\u003E is a key characteristic of fast glycolytic (type IIb) muscle fibres. These fibres have high myosin ATPase activity enabling quick contractions, but fatigue rapidly due to their reliance on anaerobic metabolism and limited mitochondrial content.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh fatigue resistance\u003C/strong\u003E - Fast glycolytic fibres fatigue quickly due to limited oxidative capacity\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELarge mitochondrial content\u003C/strong\u003E - These fibres have few mitochondria compared to oxidative fibres\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESlow myosin ATPase activity\u003C/strong\u003E - Fast glycolytic fibres have high myosin ATPase activity for rapid contractions\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPredominant oxidative metabolism\u003C/strong\u003E - These fibres rely primarily on anaerobic glycolysis for energy production\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EFast glycolytic fibres contain high levels of glycolytic enzymes and glycogen stores but low levels of oxidative enzymes and myoglobin. They are recruited for activities requiring brief, powerful contractions such as sprinting or weightlifting.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fast glycolytic (type IIb) muscle fibres have high anaerobic capacity and fatigue quickly due to limited mitochondria.","Fast glycolytic fibres contain high levels of glycolytic enzymes and low levels of oxidative enzymes.","Fast glycolytic fibres have rapid contraction speeds due to high myosin ATPase activity."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61931"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18613"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61931"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T14:04:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-03T14:04:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11345"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76434"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4931"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Musculoskeletal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}